 journals, and fiction.Featuring extensive previously unpublished images, The Arab Imago shows how native photography played an essential role in the creation of modern Arab societies in Egypt, Palestine, Syria, and Lebanon before the First World War. At the same time, the book overturns Eurocentric and Orientalist understandings of indigenous photography and challenges previous histories of the medium.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aArabsvPortraits. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspectszMiddle EastxHistoryy19th century. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspectszMiddle EastxHistoryy20th century. 0aPortrait photographyzMiddle EastxHistoryx20th century. 0aPortrait photographyzMiddle EastxHistoryy19th century. 0aPortrait photographyzMiddle EastxHistoryy20th century. 7aPhotography / History.2bisacsh  aAge of Enlightenment.  aAl-Kindi.  aAl-Mahdi.  aAl-Maqrizi.  aArab nationalism.  aBaedeker.  aBildungsroman.  aBrookes (ship).  aBruno Latour.  aButrus al-Bustani.  aCalligraphy.  aCarte de visite.  aCivilizing mission.  aColonialism.  aCommittee of Union and Progress.  aComrade.  aCultural geography.  aDaoud Corm.  aDemocritus.  aDeterritorialization.  aDipesh Chakrabarty.  aDisenchantment.  aEconomy and Society.  aEconomy of Egypt.  aEdelstein.  aEgyptology.  aEgyptomania.  aElizabeth Thompson.  aEunuch.  aFeminism (international relations).  aGertrude Bell.  aGrand Vizier.  aGustave Le Gray.  aHussein bin Ali, Sharif of Mecca.  aIdeology.  aIntelligentsia.  aJacques Derrida.  aJacques Lacan.  aJews.  aJointness (psychodynamics).  aJonathan Crary.  aJudith Butler.  aKahlil Gibran.  aKhedive.  aLas Meninas.  aLehnert & Landrock.  aLiberalism.  aLouis Daguerre.  aMax Weber.  aMetonymy.  aMiddle East.  aMidhat Pasha